Assured Service Quality by Improved Fault Management 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:The paradigm shift from device oriented to service oriented management has also implications to the area of event correlation .
1-2:Today"s event correlation mainly addresses the correlation of events as reported from management tools .
1-3:However, a correlation of user trouble reports concerning services should also be performed .
1-4:This is necessary to improve the resolution time and to reduce the effort for keeping the service agreements .
1-5:We refer to such a type of correlation as service oriented event correlation .
1-6:The necessity to use this kind of event correlation is motivated in the paper .
1-7:To introduce service oriented event correlation for an IT service provider, an appropriate modeling of the correlation workflow and of the information is necessary .
1-8:Therefore, we examine the process management frameworks IT Infrastructure Library and enhanced Telecom Operations Map (eTOM) for their contribution to the workflow modeling in this area .
1-9:The different kinds of dependencies that we find in our general scenario are then used to develop a workflow for the service oriented event correlation .
1-10:The MNM Service Model, which is a generic model for IT service management proposed by the Munich Network Management Team, is used to derive an appropriate information modeling .
1-11:An example scenario, the Web Hosting Service of the Leibniz Supercomputing Center (LRZ), is used to demonstrate the application of service oriented event correlation .
1-12:C.2.4 [Computer Systems Organization]: .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:In huge networks a single fault can cause a burst of failure events .
2-2:To handle the flood of events and to find the root cause of a fault, event correlation approaches like rule based reasoning, case based reasoning or the codebook approach have been developed .
2-3:The main idea of correlation is to condense and structure events to retrieve meaningful information .
2-4:Until now, these approaches address primarily the correlation of events as reported from management tools or devices .
2-5:Therefore, we call them device oriented .
2-6:In this paper we define a service as a set of functions which are offered by a provider to a customer at a customer provider interface .
2-7:The definition of a service is therefore more general than the definition of a Web Service, but a Web Service is included in this service definition .
2-8:As a consequence, the results are applicable for Web Services as well as for other kinds of services .
2-9:A service level agreement is defined as a contract between customer and provider about guaranteed service performance .
2-10:As in today"s IT environments the offering of such services with an agreed service quality becomes more and more important, this change also affects the event correlation .
2-11:It has become a necessity for providers to offer such guarantees for a differentiation from other providers .
2-12:To avoid SLA violations it is especially important for service providers to identify the root cause of a fault in a very short time or even act proactively .
2-13:The latter refers to the case of recognizing the influence of a device breakdown on the offered services .
2-14:As in this scenario the knowledge about services and their SLAs is used we call it service oriented .
2-15:It can be addressed from two directions .
2-16:Top down perspective: Several customers report a problem in a certain time interval .
2-17:Are these trouble reports correlated? How to identify a resource as being the problem"s root cause? 183 Bottom up perspective: A device (e.g., router, server) breaks down .
2-18:Which services, and especially which customers, are affected by this fault? The rest of the paper is organized as follows .
2-19:In Section 2 we describe how event correlation is performed today and present a selection of the state of the art event correlation techniques .
2-20:Section 3 describes the motivation for serviceoriented event correlation and its benefits .
2-21:After having motivated the need for such type of correlation we use two well known IT service management models to gain requirements for an appropriate workflow modeling and present our proposal for it (see Section 4) .
2-22:In Section 5 we present our information modeling which is derived from the MNM Service Model .
2-23:An application of the approach for a web hosting scenario is performed in Section 6 .
2-24:The last section concludes the paper and presents future work. .
3 TODAY"S EVENT CORRELATION TECHNIQUES :
3-1:TECHNIQUES In [11] the task of event correlation is defined as a conceptual interpretation procedure in the sense that a new meaning is assigned to a set of events that happen in a certain time interval .
3-2:We can distinguish between three aspects for event correlation .
3-3:Functional aspect: The correlation focuses on functions which are provided by each network element .
3-4:It is also regarded which other functions are used to provide a specific function .
3-5:Topology aspect: The correlation takes into account how the network elements are connected to each other and how they interact .
3-6:Time aspect: When explicitly regarding time constraints, a start and end time has to be defined for each event .
3-7:The correlation can use time relationships between the events to perform the correlation .
3-8:This aspect is only mentioned in some papers [11], but it has to be treated in an event correlation system .
3-9:In the event correlation it is also important to distinguish between the knowledge acquisition representation and the correlation algorithm .
3-10:Examples of approaches to knowledge acquisition representation are Gruschke"s dependency graphs [6] and Ensel"s dependency detection by neural networks [3] .
3-11:It is also possible to find the dependencies by analyzing interactions [7] .
3-12:In addition, there is an approach to manage service dependencies with XML and to define a resource description framework [4] .
3-13:To get an overview about device oriented event correlation a selection of several event correlation techniques being used for this kind of correlation is presented .
3-14:Model based reasoning: Model based reasoning [15, 10, 20] represents a system by modeling each of its components .
3-15:A model can either represent a physical entity or a logical entity (e.g., LAN, WAN, domain, service, business process) .
3-16:The models for physical entities are called functional model, while the models for all logical entities are called logical model .
3-17:A description of each model contains three categories of information: attributes, relations to other models, and behavior .
3-18:The event correlation is a result of the collaboration among models .
3-19:As all components of a network are represented with their behavior in the model, it is possible to perform simulations to predict how the whole network will behave .
3-20:A comparison in [20] showed that a large MBR system is not in all cases easy to maintain .
3-21:It can be difficult to appropriately model the behavior for all components and their interactions correctly and completely .
3-22:An example system for MBR is NetExpert[16] from OSI which is a hybrid MBR RBR system (in 2000 OSI was acquired by Agilent Technologies) .
3-23:Rule based reasoning: Rule based reasoning [15, 10] uses a set of rules for event correlation .
3-24:The rules have the form conclusion if condition .
3-25:The condition uses received events and information about the system, while the conclusion contains actions which can either lead to system changes or use system parameters to choose the next rule .
3-26:An advantage of the approach is that the rules are more or less human readable and therefore their effect is intuitive .
3-27:The correlation has proved to be very fast in practice by using the RETE algorithm .
3-28:In the literature [20, 1] it is claimed that RBR systems are classified as relatively inflexible .
3-29:Frequent changes in the modeled IT environment would lead to many rule updates .
3-30:These changes would have to be performed by experts as no automation has currently been established .
3-31:In some systems information about the network topology which is needed for the event correlation is not used explicitly, but is encoded into the rules .
3-32:This intransparent usage would make rule updates for topology changes quite difficult .
3-33:The system brittleness would also be a problem for RBR systems .
3-34:It means that the system fails if an unknown case occurs, because the case cannot be mapped onto similar cases .
3-35:The output of RBR systems would also be difficult to predict, because of unforeseen rule interactions in a large rule set .
3-36:According to [15] an RBR system is only appropriate if the domain for which it is used is small, nonchanging, and well understood .
3-37:The GTE IMPACT system [11] is an example of a rulebased system .
3-38:It also uses MBR (GTE has merged with Bell Atlantic in 1998 and is now called Verizon [19]) .
3-39:Codebook approach: The codebook approach [12, 21] has similarities to RBR, but takes a further step and encodes the rules into a correlation matrix .
3-40:The approach starts using a dependency graph with two kinds of nodes for the modeling .
3-41:The first kind of nodes are the faults (denoted as problems in the cited papers) which have to be detected, while the second kind of nodes are observable events (symptoms in the papers) which are caused by the faults or other events .
3-42:The dependencies between the nodes are denoted as directed edges .
3-43:It is possible to choose weights for the edges, e.g., a weight for the probability that 184 fault event A causes event B .
3-44:Another possible weighting could indicate time dependencies .
3-45:There are several possibilities to reduce the initial graph .
3-46:If, e.g., a cyclic dependency of events exists and there are no probabilities for the cycles" edges, all events can be treated as one event .
3-47:After a final input graph is chosen, the graph is transformed into a correlation matrix where the columns contain the faults and the rows contain the events .
3-48:If there is a dependency in the graph, the weight of the corresponding edge is put into the according matrix cell .
3-49:In case no weights are used, the matrix cells get the values 1 for dependency and 0 otherwise .
3-50:Afterwards, a simplification can be done, where events which do not help to discriminate faults are deleted .
3-51:There is a trade off between the minimization of the matrix and the robustness of the results .
3-52:If the matrix is minimized as much as possible, some faults can only be distinguished by a single event .
3-53:If this event cannot be reliably detected, the event correlation system cannot discriminate between the two faults .
3-54:A measure how many event observation errors can be compensated by the system is the Hamming distance .
3-55:The number of rows (events) that can be deleted from the matrix can differ very much depending on the relationships [15] .
3-56:The codebook approach has the advantage that it uses long term experience with graphs and coding .
3-57:This experience is used to minimize the dependency graph and to select an optimal group of events with respect to processing time and robustness against noise .
3-58:A disadvantage of the approach could be that similar to RBR frequent changes in the environment make it necessary to frequently edit the input graph .
3-59:SMARTS InCharge [12, 17] is an example of such a correlation system .
3-60:Case based reasoning: In contrast to other approaches case based reasoning [14, 15] systems do not use any knowledge about the system structure .
3-61:The knowledge base saves cases with their values for system parameters and successful recovery actions for these cases .
3-62:The recovery actions are not performed by the CBR system in the first place, but in most cases by a human operator .
3-63:If a new case appears, the CBR system compares the current system parameters with the system parameters in prior cases and tries to find a similar one .
3-64:To identify such a match it has to be defined for which parameters the cases can differ or have to be the same .
3-65:If a match is found, a learned action can be performed automatically or the operator can be informed with a recovery proposal .
3-66:An advantage of this approach is that the ability to learn is an integral part of it which is important for rapid changing environments .
3-67:There are also difficulties when applying the approach [15] .
3-68:The fields which are used to find a similar case and their importance have to be defined appropriately .
3-69:If there is a match with a similar case, an adaptation of the previous solution to the current one has to be found .
3-70:An example system for CBR is SpectroRx from Cabletron Systems .
3-71:The part of Cabletron that developed SpectroRx became an independent software company in 2002 and is now called Aprisma Management Technologies [2] .
3-72:In this section four event correlation approaches were presented which have evolved into commercial event correlation systems .
3-73:The correlation approaches have different focuses .
3-74:MBR mainly deals with the knowledge acquisition and representation, while RBR and the codebook approach propose a correlation algorithm .
3-75:The focus of CBR is its ability to learn from prior cases. .
4 MOTIVATION OF SERVICE ORIENTED EVENT CORRELATION :
4-1:EVENT CORRELATION Fig .
4-2:1 shows a general service scenario upon which we will discuss the importance of a service oriented correlation .
4-3:Several services like SSH, a web hosting service, or a video conference service are offered by a provider to its customers at the customer provider interface .
4-4:A customer can allow several users to use a subscribed service .
4-5:The quality and cost issues of the subscribed services between a customer and a provider are agreed in SLAs .
4-6:On the provider side the services use subservices for their provisioning .
4-7:In case of the services mentioned above such subservices are DNS, proxy service, and IP service .
4-8:Both services and subservices depend on resources upon which they are provisioned .
4-9:As displayed in the figure a service can depend on more than one resource and a resource can be used by one or more services .
4-10:SSH DNS proxy IP service dependency resource dependency user a user b user c customer SLA web a video conf .
4-11:SSH sun1 provider video conf .
4-12:web services subservices resources Figure 1: Scenario To get a common understanding, we distinguish between different types of events: Resource event: We use the term resource event for network events and system events .
4-13:A network event refers to events like node up down or link up down whereas system events refer to events like server down or authentication failure .
4-14:Service event: A service event indicates that a service does not work properly .
4-15:A trouble ticket which is generated from a customer report is a kind of such an 185 event .
4-16:Other service events can be generated by the provider of a service, if the provider himself detects a service malfunction .
4-17:In such a scenario the provider may receive service events from customers which indicate that SSH, web hosting service, and video conference service are not available .
4-18:When referring to the service hierarchy, the provider can conclude in such a case that all services depend on DNS .
4-19:Therefore, it seems more likely that a common resource which is necessary for this service does not work properly or is not available than to assume three independent service failures .
4-20:In contrast to a resource oriented perspective where all of the service events would have to be processed separately, the service events can be linked together .
4-21:Their information can be aggregated and processed only once .
4-22:If, e.g., the problem is solved, one common message to the customers that their services are available again is generated and distributed by using the list of linked service events .
4-23:This is certainly a simplified example .
4-24:However, it shows the general principle of identifying the common subservices and common resources of different services .
4-25:It is important to note that the service oriented perspective is needed to integrate service aspects, especially QoS aspects .
4-26:An example of such an aspect is that a fault does not lead to a total failure of a service, but its QoS parameters, respectively agreed service levels, at the customer provider interface might not be met .
4-27:A degradation in service quality which is caused by high traffic load on the backbone is another example .
4-28:In the resource oriented perspective it would be possible to define events which indicate that there is a link usage higher than a threshold, but no mechanism has currently been established to find out which services are affected and whether a QoS violation occurs .
4-29:To summarize, the reasons for the necessity of a serviceoriented event correlation are the following: Keeping of SLAs (top down perspective): The time interval between the first symptom (recognized either by provider, network management tools, or customers) that a service does not perform properly and the verified fault repair needs to be minimized .
4-30:This is especially needed with respect to SLAs as such agreements often contain guarantees like a mean time to repair .
4-31:Effort reduction (top down perspective): If several user trouble reports are symptoms of the same fault, fault processing should be performed only once and not several times .
4-32:If the fault has been repaired, the affected customers should be informed about this automatically .
4-33:Impact analysis (bottom up perspective): In case of a fault in a resource, its influence on the associated services and affected customers can be determined .
4-34:This analysis can be performed for short term (when there is currently a resource failure) or long term (e.g., network optimization) considerations. .
5 WORKFLOW MODELING :
5-1:In the following we examine the established IT process management frameworks IT Infrastructure Library and enhanced Telecom Operations Map (eTOM) .
5-2:The aim is find out where event correlation can be found in the process structure and how detailed the frameworks currently are .
5-3:After that we present our solution for a workflow modeling for the service oriented event correlation .
5-4:4.1 IT Infrastructure Library The British Office of Government Commerce and the IT Service Management Forum (itSMF) [9] provide a collection of best practices for IT processes in the area of IT service management which is called ITIL .
5-5:The service management is described by 11 modules which are grouped into Service Support Set (provider internal processes) and Service Delivery Set (processes at the customer provider interface) .
5-6:Each module describes processes, functions, roles, and responsibilities as well as necessary databases and interfaces .
5-7:In general, ITIL describes contents, processes, and aims at a high abstraction level and contains no information about management architectures and tools .
5-8:The fault management is divided into Incident Management process and Problem Management process .
5-9:Incident Management: The Incident Management contains the service desk as interface to customers (e.g., receives reports about service problems) .
5-10:In case of severe errors structured queries are transferred to the Problem Management .
5-11:Problem Management: The Problem Management"s tasks are to solve problems, take care of keeping priorities, minimize the reoccurrence of problems, and to provide management information .
5-12:After receiving requests from the Incident Management, the problem has to be identified and information about necessary countermeasures is transferred to the Change Management .
5-13:The ITIL processes describe only what has to be done, but contain no information how this can be actually performed .
5-14:As a consequence, event correlation is not part of the modeling .
5-15:The ITIL incidents could be regarded as input for the service oriented event correlation, while the output could be used as a query to the ITIL Problem Management .
5-16:4.2 Enhanced Telecom Operations Map (eTOM) The TeleManagement Forum [18] is an international non profit organization from service providers and suppliers in the area of telecommunications services .
5-17:Similar to ITIL a process oriented framework has been developed at first, but the framework was designed for a narrower focus, i.e., the market of information and communications service providers .
5-18:A horizontal grouping into processes for customer care, service development & operations, network & systems management, and partner supplier is performed .
5-19:The vertical grouping (fulfillment, assurance, billing) reflects the service life cycle .
5-20:In the area of fault management three processes have been defined along the horizontal process grouping .
5-21:Problem Handling: The purpose of this process is to receive trouble reports from customers and to solve them by using the Service Problem Management .
5-22:The aim is also to keep the customer informed about the current status of the trouble report processing as well as about the general network status (e.g., planned maintenance) .
5-23:It is also a task of this process to inform the 186 QoS SLA management about the impact of current errors on the SLAs .
5-24:Service Problem Management: In this process reports about customer affecting service failures are received and transformed .
5-25:Their root causes are identified and a problem solution or a temporary workaround is established .
5-26:The task of the Diagnose Problem subprocess is to find the root cause of the problem by performing appropriate tests .
5-27:Nothing is said how this can be done (e.g., no event correlation is mentioned) .
5-28:Resource Trouble Management: A subprocess of the Resource Trouble Management is responsible for resource failure event analysis, alarm correlation & filtering, and failure event detection & reporting .
5-29:Another subprocess is used to execute different tests to find a resource failure .
5-30:There is also another subprocess which keeps track about the status of the trouble report processing .
5-31:This subprocess is similar to the functionality of a trouble ticket system .
5-32:The process description in eTOM is not very detailed .
5-33:It is useful to have a check list which aspects for these processes have to be taken into account, but there is no detailed modeling of the relationships and no methodology for applying the framework .
5-34:Event correlation is only mentioned in the resource management, but it is not used in the service level .
5-35:4.3 Workflow Modeling for the Service Oriented Event Correlation Fig .
5-36:2 shows a general service scenario which we will use as basis for the workflow modeling for the service oriented event correlation .
5-37:We assume that the dependencies are already known (e.g., by using the approaches mentioned in Section 2) .
5-38:The provider offers different services which depend on other services called subservices (service dependency) .
5-39:Another kind of dependency exists between services subservices and resources .
5-40:These dependencies are called resource dependencies .
5-41:These two kinds of dependencies are in most cases not used for the event correlation performed today .
5-42:This resource oriented event correlation deals only with relationships on the resource level (e.g., network topology) .
5-43:service dependency resources subservices provider services resource dependency Figure 2: Different kinds of dependencies for the service oriented event correlation The dependencies depicted in Figure 2 reflect a situation with no redundancy in the service provisioning .
5-44:The relationships can be seen as AND relationships .
5-45:In case of redundancy, if e.g., a provider has 3 independent web servers, another modeling (see Figure 3) should be used (OR relationship) .
5-46:In such a case different relationships are possible .
5-47:The service could be seen as working properly if one of the servers is working or a certain percentage of them is working .
5-48:services ) AND relationship b) OR relationship resources Figure 3: Modeling of no redundancy (a) and of redundancy (b) As both ITIL and eTOM contain no description how event correlation and especially service oriented event correlation should actually be performed, we propose the following design for such a workflow (see Fig .
5-49:4) .
5-50:The additional components which are not part of a device oriented event correlation are depicted with a gray background .
5-51:The workflow is divided into the phases fault detection, fault diagnosis, and fault recovery .
5-52:In the fault detection phase resource events and service events can be generated from different sources .
5-53:The resource events are issued during the use of a resource, e.g., via SNMP traps .
5-54:The service events are originated from customer trouble reports, which are reported via the Customer Service Management (see below) access point .
5-55:In addition to these two passive ways to get the events, a provider can also perform active tests .
5-56:These tests can either deal with the resources (resource active probing) or can assume the role of a virtual customer and test a service or one of its subservices by performing interactions at the service access points (service active probing) .
5-57:The fault diagnosis phase is composed of three event correlation steps .
5-58:The first one is performed by the resource event correlator which can be regarded as the event correlator in today"s commercial systems .
5-59:Therefore, it deals only with resource events .
5-60:The service event correlator does a correlation of the service events, while the aggregate event correlator finally performs a correlation of both resource and service events .
5-61:If the correlation result in one of the correlation steps shall be improved, it is possible to go back to the fault detection phase and start the active probing to get additional events .
5-62:These events can be helpful to confirm a correlation result or to reduce the list of possible root causes .
5-63:After the event correlation an ordered list of possible root causes is checked by the resource management .
5-64:When the root cause is found, the failure repair starts .
5-65:This last step is performed in the fault recovery phase .
5-66:The next subsections present different elements of the event correlation process .
5-67:4.4 Customer Service Management and Intelligent Assistant The Customer Service Management access point was proposed by [13] as a single interface between customer 187 fault detection fault diagnosis resource active probing resource event resource event correlator resource management candidate list fault recovery resource usage service active probing intelligent assistant service event correlator aggregate event correlator service eventCSM AP Figure 4: Event correlation workflow and provider .
5-68:Its functionality is to provide information to the customer about his subscribed services, e.g., reports about the fulfillment of agreed SLAs .
5-69:It can also be used to subscribe services or to allow the customer to manage his services in a restricted way .
5-70:Reports about problems with a service can be sent to the customer via CSM .
5-71:The CSM is also contained in the MNM Service Model (see Section 5) .
5-72:To reduce the effort for the provider"s first level support, an Intelligent Assistant can be added to the CSM .
5-73:The Intelligent Assistant structures the customer"s information about a service problem .
5-74:The information which is needed for a preclassification of the problem is gathered from a list of questions to the customer .
5-75:The list is not static as the current question depends on the answers to prior questions or from the result of specific tests .
5-76:A decision tree is used to structure the questions and tests .
5-77:The tests allow the customer to gain a controlled access to the provider"s management .
5-78:At the LRZ a customer of the E Mail Service can, e.g., use the Intelligent Assistant to perform ping requests to the mail server .
5-79:But also more complex requests could be possible, e.g., requests of a combination of SNMP variables .
5-80:4.5 Active Probing Active probing is useful for the provider to check his offered services .
5-81:The aim is to identify and react to problems before a customer notices them .
5-82:The probing can be done from a customer point of view or by testing the resources which are part of the services .
5-83:It can also be useful to perform tests of subservices (own subservices or subservices offered by suppliers) .
5-84:Different schedules are possible to perform the active probing .
5-85:The provider could select to test important services and resources in regular time intervals .
5-86:Other tests could be initiated by a user who traverses the decision tree of the Intelligent Assistant including active tests .
5-87:Another possibility for the use of active probing is a request from the event correlator, if the current correlation result needs to be improved .
5-88:The results of active probing are reported via service or resource events to the event correlator (or if the test was demanded by the Intelligent Assistant the result is reported to it, too) .
5-89:While the events that are received from management tools and customers denote negative events (something does not work), the events from active probing should also contain positive events for a better discrimination .
5-90:4.6 Event Correlator The event correlation should not be performed by a single event correlator, but by using different steps .
5-91:The reason for this are the different characteristics of the dependencies (see Fig .
5-92:1) .
5-93:On the resource level there are only relationships between resources (network topology, systems configuration) .
5-94:An example for this could be a switch linking separate LANs .
5-95:If the switch is down, events are reported that other network components which are located behind the switch are also not reachable .
5-96:When correlating these events it can be figured out that the switch is the likely error cause .
5-97:At this stage, the integration of service events does not seem to be helpful .
5-98:The result of this step is a list of resources which could be the problem"s root cause .
5-99:The resource event correlator is used to perform this step .
5-100:In the service oriented scenario there are also service and resource dependencies .
5-101:As next step in the event correlation process the service events should be correlated with each other using the service dependencies, because the service dependencies have no direct relationship to the resource level .
5-102:The result of this step, which is performed by the service event correlator, is a list of services subservices which could contain a failure in a resource .
5-103:If, e.g., there are service events from customers that two services do not work and both services depend on a common subservice, it seems more likely that the resource failure can be found inside the subservice .
5-104:The output of this correlation is a list of services subservices which could be affected by a failure in an associated resource .
5-105:In the last step the aggregate event correlator matches the lists from resource event correlator and service event correlator to find the problem"s possible root cause .
5-106:This is done by using the resource dependencies .
5-107:The event correlation techniques presented in Section 2 could be used to perform the correlation inside the three event correlators .
5-108:If the dependencies can be found precisely, an RBR or codebook approach seems to be appropriate .
5-109:A case database could be used if there are cases which could not be covered by RBR or the codebook approach .
5-110:These cases could then be used to improve the modeling in a way that RBR or the codebook approach can deal with them in future correlations. .
6 INFORMATION MODELING :
6-1:In this section we use a generic model for IT service management to derive the information necessary for the event correlation process .
6-2:5.1 MNM Service Model The MNM Service Model [5] is a generic model for IT service management .
6-3:A distinction is made between customer side and provider side .
6-4:The customer side contains the basic roles customer and user, while the provider side contains the role provider .
6-5:The provider makes the service available to the customer side .
6-6:The service as a whole is divided into usage which is accessed by the role user and management which is used by the role customer .
6-7:The model consists of two main views .
6-8:The Service View (see Fig .
6-9:5) shows a common perspective of the service for customer and provider .
6-10:Everything that is only important 188 for the service realization is not contained in this view .
6-11:For these details another perspective, the Realization View, is defined (see Fig .
6-12:6) .
