6-14:There are two access points (service access point and CSM access point) where user and customer can access the usage and management functionality, respectively .
6-15:Associated to each service is a list of QoS parameters which have to be met by the service at the service access point .
6-16:The QoS surveillance is performed by the management .
6-17:provider domain implements observesrealizes provides directs implementsrealizes accesses uses concludes accesses usesuses manages side independent side independent manages manages concludes acts as service implementation service management implementation manages uses acts as service logic sub service client service client CSM client uses resources usesuses service management logic sub service management client basic management functionality «role» customer «role» provider «role» user Figure 6: Realization View In the Realization View the service implementation and the service management implementation are described in detail .
6-18:For both there are provider internal resources and subservices .
6-19:For the service implementation a service logic uses internal resources (devices, knowledge, staff) and external subservices to provide the service .
6-20:Analogous, the service management implementation includes a service management logic using basic management functionalities [8] and external management subservices .
6-21:The MNM Service Model can be used for a similar modeling of the used subservices, i.e., the model can be applied recursively .
6-22:As the service oriented event correlation has to use dependencies of a service from subservices and resources, the model is used in the following to derive the needed information for service events .
6-23:5.2 Information Modeling for Service Events Today"s event correlation deals mainly with events which are originated from resources .
6-24:Beside a resource identifier these events contain information about the resource status, e.g., SNMP variables .
6-25:To perform a service oriented event correlation it is necessary to define events which are related to services .
6-26:These events can be generated from the provider"s own service surveillance or from customer reports at the CSM interface .
6-27:They contain information about the problems with the agreed QoS .
6-28:In our information modeling we define an event superclass which contains common attributes (e.g., time stamp) .
6-29:Resource event and service event inherit from this superclass .
6-30:Derived from the MNM Service Model we define the information necessary for a service event .
6-31:Service: As a service event shall represent the problems of a single service, a unique identification of the affected service is contained here .
6-32:Event description: This field has to contain a description of the problem .
6-33:Depending on the interactions at the service access point (Service View) a classification of the problem into different categories should be defined .
6-34:It should also be possible to add an informal description of the problem .
6-35:QoS parameters: For each service QoS parameters (Service View) are defined between the provider and the customer .
6-36:This field represents a list of these QoS parameters and agreed service levels .
6-37:The list can help the provider to set the priority of a problem with respect to the service levels agreed .
6-38:Resource list: This list contains the resources (Realization View) which are needed to provide the service .
6-39:This list is used by the provider to check if one of these resources causes the problem .
6-40:Subservice service event identification: In the service hierarchy (Realization View) the service, for which this service event has been issued, may depend on subservices .
6-41:If there is a suspicion that one of these subservices causes the problem, child service events are issued from this service event for the subservices .
6-42:In such a case this field contains links to the corresponding events .
6-43:Other event identifications: In the event correlation process the service event can be correlated with other service events or with resource events .
6-44:This field then contains links to other events which have been correlated to this service event .
6-45:This is useful to, e.g., send a common message to all affected customers when their subscribed services are available again .
6-46:Issuer"s identification: This field can either contain an identification of the customer who reported the problem, an identification of a service provider"s employee 189 (in case the failure has been detected by the provider"s own service active probing) or a link to a parent service event .
6-47:The identification is needed, if there are ambiguities in the service event or the issuer should be informed (e.g., that the service is available again) .
6-48:The possible issuers refer to the basic roles (customer, provider) in the Service Model .
6-49:Assignee: To keep track of the processing the name and address of the provider"s employee who is solving or solved the problem is also noted .
6-50:This is a specialization of the provider role in the Service Model .
6-51:Dates: This field contains key dates in the processing of the service event such as initial date, problem identification date, resolution date .
6-52:These dates are important to keep track how quick the problems have been solved .
6-53:Status: This field represents the service event"s actual status (e.g., active, suspended, solved) .
6-54:Priority: The priority shows which importance the service event has from the provider"s perspective .
6-55:The importance is derived from the service agreement, especially the agreed QoS parameters (Service View) .
6-56:The fields date, status, and other service events are not derived directly from the Service Model, but are necessary for the event correlation process. .
7 APPLICATION OF  SERVICE ORIENTED EVENT CORRELATION FOR A :
7-1:SERVICE ORIENTED EVENT CORRELATION FOR A WEB HOSTING SCENARIO The Leibniz Supercomputing Center is the joint computing center for the Munich universities and research institutions .
7-2:It also runs the Munich Scientific Network and offers related services .
7-3:One of these services is the Virtual WWW Server, a web hosting offer for smaller research institutions .
7-4:It currently has approximately 200 customers .
7-5:A subservice of the Virtual WWW Server is the Storage Service which stores the static and dynamic web pages and uses caching techniques for a fast access .
7-6:Other subservices are DNS and IP service .
7-7:When a user accesses a hosted web site via one of the LRZ"s Virtual Private Networks the VPN service is also used .
7-8:The resources of the Virtual WWW Server include a load balancer and 5 redundant servers .
7-9:The network connections are also part of the resources as well as the Apache web server application running on the servers .
7-10:Figure 7 shows the dependencies of the Virtual WWW Server .
7-11:6.1 Customer Service Management and Intelligent Assistant The Intelligent Assistant that is available at the Leibniz Supercomputing Center can currently be used for connectivity or performance problems or problems with the LRZ E Mail Service .
7-12:A selection of possible customer problem reports for the Virtual WWW Server is given in the following: • The hosted web site is not reachable .
7-13:• The web site access is (too) slow .
7-14:• The web site contains outdated content .
7-15:server serverserver server server server server server server outgoing connection hosting of LRZ"s own pages content caching server emergency server webmail server dynamic web pages static web pages DNS ProxyIP Storage Resources: Services: Virtual WWW Server five redundant servers AFS NFS DBload balancer Figure 7: Dependencies of the Virtual WWW Server • The transfer of new content to the LRZ does not change the provided content .
7-16:• The web site looks strange (e.g., caused by problems with HTML version) This customer reports have to be mapped onto failures in resources .
7-17:For, e.g., an unreachable web site different root causes are possible like a DNS problem, connectivity problem, wrong configuration of the load balancer .
7-18:6.2 Active Probing In general, active probing can be used for services or resources .
7-19:For the service active probing of the Virtual WWW Server a virtual customer could be installed .
7-20:This customer does typical HTTP requests of web sites and compares the answer with the known content .
7-21:To check the up to dateness of a test web site, the content could contain a time stamp .
7-22:The service active probing could also include the testing of subservices, e.g., sending requests to the DNS .
7-23:The resource active probing performs tests of the resources .
7-24:Examples are connectivity tests, requests to application processes, and tests of available disk space .
7-25:6.3 Event Correlation for the Virtual WWW Server Figure 8 shows the example processing .
7-26:At first, a customer who takes a look at his hosted web site reports that the content that he had changed is not displayed correctly .
7-27:This report is transferred to the service management via the CSM interface .
7-28:An Intelligent Assistant could be used to structure the customer report .
7-29:The service management translates the customer report into a service event .
7-30:Independent from the customer report the service provider"s own service active probing tries to change the content of a test web site .
7-31:Because this is not possible, a service event is issued .
7-32:Meanwhile, a resource event has been reported to the event correlator, because an access of the content caching server to one of the WWW servers failed .
7-33:As there are no other events at the moment the resource event correlation 190 customer CSM service mgmt event correlator resource mgmt customer reports: "web site content not up−to−date" service active probing reports: "web site content change not possible" event: "retrieval of server content failed"event forward resource event correlation service event correlation aggregate event correlation link failure report event forward check WWW server check link result display link repair result display result forward customer report Figure 8: Example processing of a customer report cannot correlate this event to other events .
7-34:At this stage it would be possible that the event correlator asks the resource management to perform an active probing of related resources .
7-35:Both service events are now transferred to the service event correlator and are correlated .
7-36:From the correlation of these events it seems likely that either the WWW server itself or the link to the WWW server is the problem"s root cause .
7-37:A wrong web site update procedure inside the content caching server seems to be less likely as this would only explain the customer report and not the service active probing result .
7-38:At this stage a service active probing could be started, but this does not seem to be useful as this correlation only deals with the Web Hosting Service and its resources and not with other services .
7-39:After the separate correlation of both resource and service events, which can be performed in parallel, the aggregate event correlator is used to correlate both types of events .
7-40:The additional resource event makes it seem much more likely that the problems are caused by a broken link to the WWW server or by the WWW server itself and not by the content caching server .
7-41:In this case the event correlator asks the resource management to check the link and the WWW server .
7-42:The decision between these two likely error causes can not be further automated here .
7-43:Later, the resource management finds out that a broken link is the failure"s root cause .
7-44:It informs the event correlator about this and it can be determined that this explains all previous events .
7-45:Therefore, the event correlation can be stopped at this point .
7-46:Depending on the provider"s customer relationship management the finding of the root cause and an expected repair time could be reported to the customers .
7-47:After the link has been repaired, it is possible to report this event via the CSM interface .
7-48:Even though many details of this event correlation process could also be performed differently, the example showed an important advantage of the service oriented event correlation .
7-49:The relationship between the service provisioning and the provider"s resources is explicitly modeled .
7-50:This allows a mapping of the customer report onto the provider internal resources .
7-51:6.4 Event Correlation for Different Services If a provider like the LRZ offers several services the serviceoriented event correlation can be used to reveal relationships that are not obvious in the first place .
7-52:If the LRZ E Mail Service and its events are viewed in relationship with the events for the Virtual WWW Server, it is possible to identify failures in common subservices and resources .
7-53:Both services depend on the DNS which means that customer reports like I cannot retrieve new e mail and The web site of my research institute is not available can have a common cause, e.g., the DNS does not work properly. .
8-1:In our paper we showed the need for a service oriented event correlation
8-2:For an IT service provider this new kind of event correlation makes it possible to automatically map problems with the current service quality onto resource failures
8-3:This helps to find the failure"s root cause earlier and to reduce costs for SLA violations
8-4:In addition, customer reports can be linked together and therefore the processing effort can be reduced
8-5:To receive these benefits we presented our approach for performing the service oriented event correlation as well as a modeling of the necessary correlation information
8-6:In the future we are going to apply our workflow and information modeling for services offered by the Leibniz Supercomputing Center going further into details
8-7:Several issues have not been treated in detail so far, e.g., the consequences for the service oriented event correlation if a subservice is offered by another provider
8-8:If a service does not perform properly, it has to be determined whether this is caused by the provider himself or by the subservice
8-9:In the latter case appropriate information has to be exchanged between the providers via the CSM interface
8-10:Another issue is the use of active probing in the event correlation process which can improve the result, but can also lead to a correlation delay
8-11:Another important point is the precise definition of dependency which has also been left out by many other publications
8-12:To avoid having to much dependencies in a certain situation one could try to check whether the dependencies currently exist
8-13:In case of a download from a web site there is only a dependency from the DNS subservice at the beginning, but after the address is resolved a download failure is unlikely to have been caused by the DNS
8-14:Another possibility to reduce the dependencies is to divide a service into its possible user interactions (e.g., an e mail service into transactions like get mail, sent mail, etc) and to define the dependencies for each user interaction
